Section 1 - Name: The name of the organization chapter shall be: “Michigan State University (MSU) Society of Hispanic
Professional Engineers (SHPE)” hereafter referred to as “MSU SHPE”.
Section 2 - Purpose: To empower the Latino population in the Michigan State Campus as well as in the Greater Lansing
area in the areas of Science, Technology, Engineering, and Mathematics by providing the resources to encourage a
pursuit of a STEM career as well as assisting with the retention of such career paths by being role models.

svg.text: Article II - National Mission, Vision, Values and Five Pillars

text.tspan: The missions and visions of SHPE National and the MSU SHPE are statements that define and provide insight for the
overall objectives and goals for both the society and chapter as a whole. The values and the five pillars of SHPE were
developed in accordance with the mission and vision of SHPE.
Mission: “SHPE changes lives by empowering the Hispanic community to realize its’ fullest potential and to impact the
world through STEM awareness, access, support, and development.”
Vision: “SHPE's vision is a world where Hispanics are highly valued and influential as the leading innovators, scientists,
mathematicians, and engineers.”
Values: We are brought together by heritage, social responsibility, and a desire to improve the lives of all people through
the use of science and technology through integrity, empowerment, achievement, diversity, and continuous self
improvement.
Five Pillars: In accordance with the national mission and vision, the five pillars of The Society of Hispanic Professional
Engineers are:
1. Academic Excellence: Support SHPE members by informing and guiding scholars through undergraduate studies,
undergraduate research, graduate school, GPA difficulties,and other academic programs.
2. Professional Development: Transforming students into competent corporate members of society by resume building,
increase in character, and efficient communication.
3. Leadership Development: Influence SHPE members to become goal-oriented team leading innovative scholars.
4. Community Outreach: Latino Community influence to the community, exciting the East Lansing and neighboring
regions through educational programs triggered to move Latino communities into STEM careers.
5. Chapter Development: Fostering meaningful connections through cultural awareness and increasing excitement in
STEM majors.
There are three MSU SHPE members: General, Executive, and Corporate Members. MSU SHPE will not discriminate on
the basis of age, color, gender, gender identity, disability status, height, marital status, national origin, political persuasion,
race, religion, sexual orientation, veteran status, or weight. Also, only MSU students may be officers and/or voting
members. Each type of member supports and uplifts the national SHPE mission. MSU SHPE recognizes each according to
the following descriptions:
General Members: General members are dedicated individuals that attend general meetings and national initiative events
such as Noche de Ciencias, and the National SHPE conference.
Executive Members: Executive members grasp and clarify the vision/mission to encourage according to the 5 SHPE pillars,
and attend 80% of executive meetings, general meetings, and national events such as Noche de Ciencias, and the
National SHPE conference.
Corporate Members: Corporate members are companies that commit themselves into a long-term relationship with MSU
SHPE through sponsorship, resume critiques, and other outreach events.
A variety of meetings throughout the year will be hosted by MSU SHPE. Meetings are subject to change every year. This
section shall describe and outline the types of meetings, which are held during a typical academic year. Meetings shall
consist of predetermined times when MSU SHPE chapter members gather to discuss various goals, tasks, events, and
other information necessary to keep the chapter connected and active.
Section 1 - Executive Board Member Meetings: The Executive Board shall meet once a week at a time convenient to the
Executive Quorum (all executive members).
Section 2 - General Meetings: The entire organization shall meet on a weekly basis during the regular semester. During
these meetings activities and plans will be discussed. If any workshops or guest speakers are available, they shall hold
the entire general meeting.
Section 3 - Social, Academic, Committee Meetings: Social, academic, and various committee meetings and events may
occur on a basis that strengthens the organization according to the Chapter Development pillar established by the Master
Calendar.

svg.text: Article V - Officer Positions and Reponsibilities

text.tspan: There are a variety of officer positions that operate cohesively within MSU SHPE to maintain the mission and visions
within the chapter. The positions listed are required to run the chapter effectively. Other roles may be added at the
executive board’s discretion. This section outlines each of these positions and the respective responsibilities of each. MSU
SHPE desires well-rounded candidates that lead general members into professionalism and academic excellence, and work
in team by brainstorming and organizing events. The following are the qualification for all executive member and
additional qualification for president and vice president.
1. Be full-time Michigan State University scholar pursuing a STEM career
2. Possess above a Cumulative 3.00 GPA
3. Be registered as an officer with the SHPE National Chapter
4. Be familiar with the SHPE bylaws
Section 1 – President Roles and Responsibilities
The Presidential Candidate(s):
1. Must be a full time Michigan State University scholar that has been accepted to the their respected STEM College.
2. Must not be an officer in any other student organization.
3. Must have at least two semesters on the executive board.
The President must be capable of fulfilling the following general roles and responsibilities:
a) Oversee the successful execution of programs by the executive board which in turn encourages the members to
finish their engineering and science studies.
b) Represent the chapter by maintaining monthly communication with the Regional Student Representative through
Fall and Spring conference calls.
Be part of the Regional Council along with the SHPE Regional Vice President, SHPE Regional student Representative,
and other SHPE representatives in the region.
Attend National Institute Leadership Developement (NILA) Conference or anticipate to during summer.
c) Increase awareness and support for SHPE and its mission within the local community.
Aspire to work with local high school(s) and SHPE Jr. Chapter president(s) to foster a strong relationship between
current and future members.
d) Be one of the two people (the other being the Treasurer) responsible to sign any documents related to financial
matters.
e) Preside at chapter board, general, and special meetings.
f) Ensure that chapter members have paid their membership and are receiving benefits from MSU SHPE, and SHPE
National programs and events throughout the year.
g) Provide SHPE National with the National Report (NRP) of the most up to date information about the chapter.
Write and sign NRP cover letter along with the adviser’s signature.
Write the NRP overall summary/conclusion.
h) Establish important partnerships with local corporate sponsors and community organizations in matters of
common interest.
i) Order graduation stoles 60 days before graduation date
j) Assure all S.M.A.R.T. Goals/Objectives are accomplished from NRP
k) Yearly register SHPE as a recognized student organization with Student Services in the fall semester
